There is no excessive or misplaced affection here3 it is all founded in fact: while everywhere and throughout it all, affection— a love that is wonderful—meets us first and leaves us last, giving form and substance and grace, and the breath of life and love, to everything that the poet’s thick-coming fancies so exquisitely frame. We can recall few poems approaching to it in this quality of sustained affection.
